<p><strong>Weird Fiction and SF</strong></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>H.P. Lovecraft, <em>The Shadow over Innsmouth</em><br />
Virgilio Pi√±era, <em>Cold Tales</em><br />
Jorge Luis Borges, <em>Labyrinths</em><br />
Philip K Dick, <em>VALIS</em><br />
Ursula K Le Guin, <em>The Left Hand of Darkness</em><br />
<em>Excavate! The Wonderful and Frightening World of The Fall</em><br />
H.P. Lovecraft, ‚ÄúNotes on Writing Weird Fiction‚Äù. <a href="https://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/essays/nwwf.aspx">Available here</a></p>
</blockquote>

<p><em>The Outsider ‚Ä¢ WIRE #183 ‚Ä¢ May 1999‚Äî</em><br />
<em>Tom Herrington interviews Mark E Smith‚Äî</em></p>

<p><strong>TH:</strong> In the past, I begin, you‚Äôve mentioned that you like composers such as Schoenberg and Stockhausen. I was wondering whether you picked up on that stuff from reading Philip K Dick, who was a big fan of that kind of music, and would drop subliminal references to it into his books. Were you aware of that connection?</p>

<p><strong>MES:</strong> That‚Äôs interesting. No, I never knew that, but it explains a lot, because his stuff was so layered at times, like 15 things going on at once in some books. I‚Äôve seen biographies of Dick and I‚Äôve had to put them away, because it‚Äôs horrible. It breaks your heart, the shit he had to put up with: bumming meals off students, things like that, just to live, and that was just before he died. I go on about not getting any royalties, but he got nothing. They pissed around with <em>Blade Runner</em> for about five years before it came out, kept changing the script, and he‚Äôs broke, health‚Äôs gone, just wondering where he‚Äôs going to get something to eat, and he dies like a fortnight before <em>Blade Runner</em> comes out. So I‚Äôm not that bad off.</p>

<p><strong>TH:</strong> Dick, like a lot of the writers you‚Äôve said you admire, was interested in the notion of psychic time travel; attempting to decipher the present by intercutting it with past and future events, which has been a theme in a lot of your work.</p>

<p><strong>MES:</strong> Pre-cog he used to call it. That‚Äôs happened to me so many times. I‚Äôve had a dream, or think I‚Äôve seen something in the paper about an event, and six months later I‚Äôll see it. It‚Äôs weird. You won‚Äôt believe this, but I remember the last time we toured Yugoslavia, I said to the band, ‚ÄúSomething‚Äôs going to happen here‚Äù. They said, ‚ÄúWhy? It‚Äôs lovely‚Äù. But I could feel it. I could feel it. I could bloody‚Ä¶ I could virtually see it, in the audience, above the audience. I‚Äôd come off stage, and say, ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs fucking weird that audience‚Äù. I‚Äôd never been frightened by an audience, you know? The group go, ‚ÄúNo, it‚Äôs great, the birds are lovely‚Äù and all that. And it was; they‚Äôre better dressed than us. But every time I went out I got in trouble with the police or a soldier; every fucking time. I got stopped; I got chased by soldiers once. I thought: there‚Äôs something going on here, I don‚Äôt like it, you know what I mean? [‚Ä¶] I‚Äôd be talking to somebody and think they were crying. They weren‚Äôt.</p>

<p><strong>MES:</strong> [<em>laughing</em>] It‚Äôs weird isn‚Äôt it? I don‚Äôt like that too much. I don‚Äôt have that so much now. It used to shit me up when I was a teenager. [<em>He shivers a little</em>] Some things are better you don‚Äôt know; don‚Äôt want to know. Don‚Äôt want to forecast or hear about.</p>

<p><br /></p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Marxism and Historical Materialism</strong></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Marx and Engels, <em>The German Ideology</em><br />
